  <processinfo id="02a61733e04bc2cde6b7b0c373e2d64b">
    <head>Processing Information</head>
<p>Level 1 Minimal Processing has been conducted to establish basic intellectual and physical control of the material and assess immediate preservation and conservation needs. Material remains as received, in original folders and storage boxes.</p><p>
Level 3 standard processsing was completed for the 2018:061 accession of Richard Magat office files. This material was processed by Darren Young in September 2018.</p>  </processinfo>
  <acqinfo id="23bf0ab739f6cbb16bd59c2e1466b1c6">
    <head>Immediate Source of Acquisition</head>
<p>Ford Foundation archive was deposited at RAC in 2011. Ford Foundation records, correspondence, reports, program files and officers papers were transferred to, and accessioned by, RAC beginning in 2011. Accessions continue as necessary.</p><p>
An additional group of Richard Magat office files was transferred to the RAC by the Ford Foundation in 2018 and was ingested by the RAC as Accession 2018:061. This accession was incorporated into the collection during processing in 2018.</p>  </acqinfo>
  <accessrestrict id="7c95d0d9b375d30b49e70ad32354802f">
    <head>Conditions Governing Access</head>
<p>Open for research. Brittle or damaged items are available at the discretion of RAC.</p>  </accessrestrict>
  <arrangement id="422f2922e9e8ff8335a22f9d5c9cb7c8">
    <head>Arrangement</head>
<p>Arranged in 4 series by file type.</p><p>Original order has been retained.</p><p>Collection arrangement is as follows:</p><p>Series 1. Chronological Correspondence, 1974-1979</p><p>Series 2. Memoranda and Publications, 1967-1973</p><p>Series 3. Publications, 1964-1992</p><p>Series 4. Subject Files, 1952-1980</p>  </arrangement>
  <scopecontent id="54495215eb4444244137da276b518cd1">
    <head>Scope and Contents</head>
<p>Contains correspondence, memoranda, publications and subject files.</p><p>Collection consists of more than one accession of Richard Magat office files ingested by the RAC over the years. An accession processed in 2018 consisted of a group of subject files regarding different press, publications, and public relations topics and was added to the end of the Subject Files series in order to reconstitute the relationship between the materials.</p><p>The RAC holds another Ford Foundation, Office of Reports, Office Files of Richard Magat collection. A more deliberate collection arrangement appears to have been imposed on this set of material during processing. Therefore, it was decided not to integrate the 2018 accession with that collection or to merge the two collections together. The finding aid for FA728 of Ford Foundation, Office of Reports, Office Files of Richard Magat can be accessed <extref xlink:href="../FA728/overview">here</extref> .</p>  </scopecontent>
  <bioghist id="9206b6bba122d056ea975478369ba6c6">
    <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
<p>Richard Magat was a member of the Ford Foundation staff from 1957 until 1982. Throughout his career at the Foundation Mr. Magat worked in the Office of Reports. He held the following positions: </p><p>April 1957, Writer </p><p>October 1957, Program Assistant </p><p>May 1958, Director </p><p>March 1968, Director and Editor </p><p>January 1982, Director (part time) </p><p>As Director and Editor, Mr. Magat was responsible for: preparing press releases, writing notes to editors and drafting letters to congressmen; writing and editing Foundation publications and articles including the Annual Report, Current Interests, and Ford Foundation Letter; recommending public reports on Foundation activity; responding to media inquiries and arranging press conferences; and administering the Office of Reports.</p><p>Mr. Magat also held the following positions:</p><p>1947-51, Dayton Daily News, Ohio, The Binghamton Sun, New York, Reporter </p><p>1951-52, McGraw-Hill Book Company, Editor in Technical Writing Service</p><p>1952-53, Paramount News, Script Writer </p><p>1953-57, New York University, Senior News Writer, Office of Information Services </p><p>1967, Mayor's Advisory Panel on Decentralization of NYC Schools, Special Assistant </p><p>1969, SUNY (Mount Vernon) Cooperative College, Instructor </p><p>1975, Joint Committee for the Reappraisal of the Role of the Red Cross, Editor </p><p>1979, SUNY (New York) Fashion Institute of Technology, Instructor </p><p>Mr. Magat was born January 1, 1927. He received his A.B. degree in 1947 from New York University. Mr. Magat took additional courses at Columbia University, New York University and the New School. Mr. Magat is the author of Ford Foundation at Work, New York: Plenum (1979), and As Others See Us, Geneva: Henry Dumant Institute (1975). He also wrote articles for Saturday Review, Consumer Reports, Trans-action and other magazines and journals. Mr. Magat left the Ford Foundation in September 1982 to become President of the Edward W. Hazen Foundation. </p>  </bioghist>
